2020-05-29 11:36:00-05:00,"You can file for a tax extension that pushes your deadline to October, but tax payments are due on July 15","The deadline to file your federal taxes and make payments is July 15, 2020. If you don't think you can get everything together to file your tax return by then, you can file for a tax extension. A tax extension pushes your filing deadline to file to October 15, but you still need to pay what you owe by July 15 or accrue interest and/or a penalty, barring any further IRS relief. You can file for an extension through one of the IRS' free filing partners, send in a form by mail, or make a payment on the IRS website for your estimated tax. See Business Insider's picks for the best tax software » The IRS postponed the deadline for federal tax returns and payments to July 15 — 90 days past the original tax-day deadline. If you can't get everything together in time for the deadline, you can file for a tax extension with the IRS, which pushes the due date for your return back six months from the original April deadline to October 15. Keep in mind that any federal tax payment you owe is due by July 15, regardless of whether you get an extension on your tax return.",HRB,en,Business Insider
